{{Infobox ancient site |name = Amuk, Amuq, Amouq |native_name = |alternate_name = |image = |alt = |caption = |map_type = Turkey |map_alt = |map_size = 200 |location =[[Antakya]], [[Turkey]] |region = |coordinates = {{coord|36.33|36.33|display=inline}} |type = Cluster of [[Tell (archaeology)|Tell]]s |part_of = |length = |width = |area = |height = |builder = |material = |built = |abandoned = |epochs = [[PPNB]], [[Neolithic]] |cultures = |dependency_of = |occupants = |event = |excavations = |archaeologists = |condition = Ruins |ownership = |management = |public_access = Yes |website = |notes = }} The '''Amik''', '''Amuk''', or '''Amuq''' '''Valley''' ({{lang-ar|الأعماق}} ''al-A’maq'') is located in the southern part of [[Turkey]], in the [[Hatay Province]], close to the city of [[Antakya]] ([[Antioch]] on the Orontes). Along with [[Dabiq, Syria|Dabiq]] in north western [[Syria]], it is believed to be one of the future sites of the battle of [[Armageddon]] according to [[Islamic eschatology]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.kerimusta.com/melhame-i-kubra-armageddon-savasi/ |title=MELHAME-İ KÜBRA (ARMAGEDDON) SAVAŞI |access-date=2015-09-11 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151212102010/http://www.kerimusta.com/melhame-i-kubra-armageddon-savasi/ |archive-date=2015-12-12 |dead-url=yes |df= }}</ref><ref>[http://hadislerde-mehdi.blogspot.com.tr/2014/08/melhame-i-kubra-ve-amik-ovas-gercegi.html Amik Ovası ve Armageddon Savaşı {{tr}}]</ref><ref>[http://www.yeniakit.com.tr/yazarlar/abdurrahman-dilipak/isidin-nihai-hedefi-7940.html IŞİD’in nihai hedefi {{tr}}]</ref><ref>[http://gaybihaberleri.blogspot.com.tr/2013/02/melhame-i-kubra-buyuk-savas.html MELHAME-İ KÜBRA / BÜYÜK SAVAŞ {{tr}}]</ref><ref>[http://www.yazete.com/genc-kalemler/mesut-akbaba/buyuk-savas-melhamei-kubra/2191/ Büyük savaş melhamei kübra {{tr}}]</ref>
It is notable for a series of archaeological sites in the "plain of Antioch".<ref>{{cite book|author1=Robert John Braidwood|author2=Richard C. Haines|author3=Linda S. Braidwood|title=Excavations in the Plain of Antioch|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=mGNiAAAAMAAJ|accessdate=24 March 2011|year=1971|publisher=University of Chicago Press}}</ref> The primary sites of the series are [[Tell al-Judaidah]], [[Çatalhöyük (Amuq)]] (not to be confused with [[Çatalhöyük]] in Anatolia), [[Tell Tayinat]], [[Tell Kurdu]], [[Alalakh]], and [[Tell Judaidah#Tell Dhahab|Tell Dhahab]].<ref>{{cite book|author1=Robert John Braidwood|author2=Richard C. Haines|author3=Linda S. Braidwood|title=Excavations in the Plain of Antioch: The structural remains of the later phases, Chatal Hüyük, Tell Al-Judaidah, and Tell Taʻyinat, by R.C. Haines|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=d3mRQAAACAAJ|accessdate=24 March 2011|date=August 1971|publisher=University of Chicago Press|isbn=9780226621982}}</ref> Tell Judaidah was surveyed by Robert Braidwood and excavated by C. MacEwan of the Oriental Institute of the [[University of Chicago]] in the 1930s.<ref name="Swain1950">{{cite book|author=Joseph Ward Swain|title=The ancient world|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=FOIfAAAAMAAJ|accessdate=24 March 2011|year=1950|publisher=Harper}}</ref><ref name="CiggaarMetcalf2006">{{cite book|author1=Krijna Nelly Ciggaar|author2=David Michael Metcalf|title=East and West in the Medieval Eastern Mediterrean: Antioch from the Byzantine reconquest until the end of the Crusader principality|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=DO8qTYM71tQC&pg=PA323|accessdate=24 March 2011|year=2006|publisher=Peeters Publishers|isbn=9789042917354|pages=323–}}</ref>
==Islamic Eschatology== [[Abu Hurayrah]], a [[sahabi|companion]] of the [[Prophet Muhammad]], reported in a [[hadith]] that the Prophet said:
{{quote|The Last Hour would not come until the Romans land at al-A’maq or in Dabiq. An army consisting of the best (soldiers) of the people of Earth at that time will come from [[Medina]] (to counteract them).<ref>[http://www.theonlyquran.com/hadith/Sahih-Muslim/?volume=41&chapter=9 Sahih-Muslim Hadith, Vol. 41, Chap. 9, Hadith 6924, per Abu Huraira] from Quran/Hadith study site: [http://www.theonlyquran.com/index.php The Only Quran]. Retrieved 16 November 2014</ref>}}
[[Islamic scholar]]s and hadith commentators suggest that the word ''Romans'' refers to Christians.<ref>{{cite book|author1=Farzana Hassan|title=Prophecy and the Fundamentalist Quest: An Integrative Study of Christian and Muslim Apocalyptic Religion|date=15 Jan 2008|publisher=McFarland|isbn=9780786480791|page=41|edition=illustrated}}<!--|accessdate=25 February 2015--></ref> The hadith further relates the subsequent Muslim victory, followed by the peaceful takeover of [[Constantinople]] with invocations of [[takbir]] and [[tasbih]], and finally the defeat of the [[Masih ad-Dajjal|Anti-Christ]] following the return and descent of [[Jesus in Islam|Jesus Christ]].<ref>{{cite book|author1=Farzana Hassan|title=Prophecy and the Fundamentalist Quest: An Integrative Study of Christian and Muslim Apocalyptic Religion|date=15 Jan 2008|publisher=McFarland|isbn=9780786480791|pages=41–2|edition=illustrated}}<!--|accessdate=25 February 2015--></ref><ref>{{cite book|author1=Muhammad Saed Abdul-Rahman|title=The Meaning and Explanation of the Glorious Qur'an (Vol 2)|date=2009|publisher=MSA Publication Limited|isbn=9781861797667|pages=311–12|edition=2}}<!--|accessdate=25 February 2015--></ref> Other hadiths relate the appearance of [[Imam Mahdi]] immediately before the [[Second Coming of Jesus]].<ref>Sonn (2004) p. 209</ref>
